% @category: General Typesetting
% @name: Layout Primitives
% @description: Boxes, rules, and spatial arrangement
@cassilda: layout_guide
  ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
  ║                              Layout Primitives                               ║
  ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
  
  Everything you see on screen is ultimately arranged by 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες‘s box model. Prose
  flows into paragraphs automatically, but when you need precise spatial control –
  columns, gutters, frames, aligned regions – you reach for the layout  primitives
  directly.  Tables, lists, frames, and most  ::stdlib macros are  built on top of
  these primitives.
  
  This guide covers the core layout system from the ground up.
  
  𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐁𝐨𝐱 𝐌𝐨𝐝𝐞𝐥
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  𝐻𝑦𝑎δες arranges content using two kinds of boxes:
  
    ● 𝐡𝐛𝐨𝐱 (horizontal box): children are placed side by side, left to right
    ● 𝐯𝐛𝐨𝐱 (vertical box): children are stacked top to bottom
  
  Every box is opened  with \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛 and  closed with \𝑒𝑛𝑑. Inside a box, each piece
  of content is wrapped in a \𝑐ℎ𝑖𝑙𝑑:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin{hbox}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \child[20]{Left column}                                           │
  │ 3:  │      \child[20]{Right column}                                          │
  │ 4:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ Left column         Right column
  
  [End out Output]
  
  In the example above, the hbox contains two  children, each 20 columns wide. The
  content flows within each child independently.
  
  A vbox stacks children vertically:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin[30]{vbox}                                                      │
  │ 2:  │      \child{First row of content}                                      │
  │ 3:  │      \child{Second row of content}                                     │
  │ 4:  │      \child{Third row of content}                                      │
  │ 5:  │  \end{vbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ First row of content
  ░ Second row of content
  ░ Third row of content
  
  [End out Output]
  
  Notice  the [30] after \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛 – that sets the vbox width to 30 columns.  Without
  it, the box inherits the parent width.
  
  
  textbf{The
  child Command}
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  \𝑐ℎ𝑖𝑙𝑑 is the building block inside boxes. It accepts up to two optional bracket
  arguments:
  
                       ┌───────────────────────────────────┐
                       │ \child[width][alignment]{content} │
                       └───────────────────────────────────┘
                                       Width
                                     o═══════o
  
  The width can be:
  
    ● A 𝐧𝐮𝐦𝐛𝐞𝐫: fixed width in columns
    ● 𝐚𝐮𝐭𝐨: expands to fill remaining space
    ● 𝐎𝐦𝐢𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐝: inherits the parent box width (in vbox) or gets equal share (in
      hbox)
  
  When multiple children use auto width, the remaining space is distributed  equa-
  lly among them:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin[40]{hbox}                                                      │
  │ 2:  │      \child[10]{Fixed}                                                 │
  │ 3:  │      \child[auto]{Fills the rest}                                      │
  │ 4:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ Fixed     Fills the rest
  
  [End out Output]
  
                                     Alignment
                                   o═══════════o
  
  The second bracket controls horizontal alignment within the child:
  
    ● 𝐥𝐞𝐟𝐭 (default): left-aligned
    ● 𝐜𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐫: centered
    ● 𝐫𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭: right-aligned
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin[30]{vbox}                                                      │
  │ 2:  │      \child[left]{Left}                                                │
  │ 3:  │      \child[center]{Center}                                            │
  │ 4:  │      \child[right]{Right}                                              │
  │ 5:  │  \end{vbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ Left
  ░             Center
  ░                          Right
  
  [End out Output]
  
  Both parameters can be combined:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin[40]{hbox}                                                      │
  │ 2:  │      \child[20][right]{Right-aligned}                                  │
  │ 3:  │      \child[20][center]{Centered}                                      │
  │ 4:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░        Right-aligned      Centered
  
  [End out Output]
  
                             Vertical Alignment in hbox
                           o════════════════════════════o
  
  When  children in an hbox have  different heights, you can control vertical ali-
  gnment with the \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛 bracket:
  
    ● \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛[top]{hbox}: align children to the top (default)
    ● \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛[middle]{hbox}: center children vertically
    ● \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛[bottom]{hbox}: align children to the bottom
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin[bottom]{hbox}                                                  │
  │ 2:  │      \child[20]{Short}                                                 │
  │ 3:  │      \child[20]{This child                                             │
  │ 4:  │  has three                                                             │
  │ 5:  │  lines}                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ Short               This child has three
  ░                     lines
  
  [End out Output]
  
  
  textbf{Horizontal Rules (
  hrule)}
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  A horizontal rule draws a line across the available width. The full syntax is:
  
                        ┌──────────────────────────────────┐
                        │ \hrule[width]{left}{fill}{right} │
                        └──────────────────────────────────┘
    ● 𝐰𝐢𝐝𝐭𝐡: number or 𝑎𝑢𝑡𝑜 (fills parent)
    ● 𝐥𝐞𝐟𝐭: left cap character(s)
    ● 𝐟𝐢𝐥𝐥: repeated fill character
    ● 𝐫𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭: right cap character(s)
  
  All  arguments are  optional. A bare  \ℎ𝑟𝑢𝑙𝑒 draws a line with the  default fill
  character:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \hrule                                                                │
  │ 2:  │                                                                        │
  │ 3:  │  \hrule[20]{<}{=}{>}                                                   │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  \hrule[20]{[}{.}{]}                                                   │
  │ 6:  │                                                                        │
  │ 7:  │  \hrule[20]{o}{═}{o}                                                   │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░   ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ░   <==================>
  ░
  ░   [..................]
  ░
  ░   o══════════════════o
  
  [End out Output]
  
  Inside a vbox, an 𝑎𝑢𝑡𝑜-width hrule stretches to the box width:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin[30]{vbox}                                                      │
  │ 2:  │      \child{Some content above}                                        │
  │ 3:  │      \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}                                       │
  │ 4:  │      \child{Some content below}                                        │
  │ 5:  │  \end{vbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ Some content above
  ░ ──────────────────────────────
  ░ Some content below
  
  [End out Output]
  
  
  textbf{Vertical Rules (
  vrule)}
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  A vertical  rule draws a line down the  height of the  available space. The full
  syntax is:
  
                        ┌──────────────────────────────────┐
                        │ \vrule[width]{top}{fill}{bottom} │
                        └──────────────────────────────────┘
    ● 𝐰𝐢𝐝𝐭𝐡: fixed or 𝑎𝑢𝑡𝑜
    ● 𝐭𝐨𝐩: top cap character
    ● 𝐟𝐢𝐥𝐥: repeated fill character
    ● 𝐛𝐨𝐭𝐭𝐨𝐦: bottom cap character
  
  When  placed in an hbox with auto  height, the vrule  stretches to match the ta-
  llest sibling:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin{hbox}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{╭}{│}{╰}}                                  │
  │ 3:  │      \child[20]{Line one                                               │
  │ 4:  │  Line two                                                              │
  │ 5:  │  Line three}                                                           │
  │ 6:  │      \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{╮}{│}{╯}}                                  │
  │ 7:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ ╭Line  one  Line  two╮
  ░ ╰Line three          ╯
  
  [End out Output]
  
  This  is, in fact,  exactly how the  \𝑓𝑟𝑎𝑚𝑒 stdlib macro works  internally – two
  vrules on the  sides, two hrules on the top and  bottom, and the  content in the
  middle.
  
  
  𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐛𝐢𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐡𝐛𝐨𝐱 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐯𝐛𝐨𝐱
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Real layouts nest boxes. A common pattern is an hbox of columns, each containing
  a vbox:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin[40]{hbox}                                                      │
  │ 2:  │      \child[20]{                                                       │
  │ 3:  │          \begin{vbox}                                                  │
  │ 4:  │              \child{Header A}                                          │
  │ 5:  │              \child{\hrule}                                            │
  │ 6:  │              \child{Data 1}                                            │
  │ 7:  │              \child{Data 2}                                            │
  │ 8:  │          \end{vbox}                                                    │
  │ 9:  │      }                                                                 │
  │ 10: │      \child[20]{                                                       │
  │ 11: │          \begin{vbox}                                                  │
  │ 12: │              \child{Header B}                                          │
  │ 13: │              \child{\hrule}                                            │
  │ 14: │              \child{Data 3}                                            │
  │ 15: │              \child{Data 4}                                            │
  │ 16: │          \end{vbox}                                                    │
  │ 17: │      }                                                                 │
  │ 18: │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ Header A            Header B
  ░ ────────────────────────────────────────
  ░ Data 1              Data 3
  ░ Data 2              Data 4
  
  [End out Output]
  
  The  \𝑡𝑎𝑏𝑙𝑒 system macro  generates exactly this  kind of nested box  structure,
  with added frame characters and junction handling.
  
  
  textbf{Junction Handling (
  intersect_rules)}
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  When horizontal and vertical rules cross, their characters must be replaced with
  proper junction characters. The  \𝑖𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑒𝑐𝑡_𝑟𝑢𝑙𝑒𝑠 command does this  automatica-
  lly:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \intersect_rules{                                                     │
  │ 2:  │  \begin[20]{vbox}                                                      │
  │ 3:  │      \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}                                       │
  │ 4:  │      \child{                                                           │
  │ 5:  │          \begin{hbox}                                                  │
  │ 6:  │              \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}                            │
  │ 7:  │              \child[auto]{Cell A}     │                                │
  │ 8:  │              \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}                            │
  │ 9:  │              \child[auto]{Cell B}     │                                │
  │ 10: │              \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}                            │
  │ 11: │          \end{hbox}                                                    │
  │ 12: │      }                                                                 │
  │ 13: │      \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}                                       │
  │ 14: │  \end{vbox}                                                            │
  │ 15: │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ ┌─────────┬────────┐
  ░ │Cell A   │Cell B  │
  ░ └─────────┴────────┘
  
  [End out Output]
  
  Without  \𝑖𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑒𝑐𝑡_𝑟𝑢𝑙𝑒𝑠, the ─ and │ characters would overlap rather than form
  proper ┌ ┬ ┐ ├ ┼ ┤ └ ┴ ┘ junctions.  The junction fixup  pass scans every  cell,
  checks its four neighbors for line arms, and replaces the character with the co-
  rrect junction glyph.
  
  This works with  single, double, bold, and mixed line styles. It also  preserves
  intentionally-placed  characters (like rounded  corners ╭ ╮ ╰ ╯) when their arms
  already match the expected junction.
  
  
  𝐌𝐞𝐚𝐬𝐮𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐧𝐭
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  The  \𝑚𝑒𝑎𝑠𝑢𝑟𝑒 command renders  content in an invisible  infinite space, measures
  its dimensions, and stores it for later recall:
  
                            ┌──────────────────────────┐
                            │ \measure<c,w,h>{content} │
                            └──────────────────────────┘
    ● 𝐜: name under which the rendered content is stored
    ● 𝐰: variable receiving the measured width
    ● 𝐡: variable receiving the measured height
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \measure<box,w,h>{Hello, World!}                                      │
  │ 2:  │                                                                        │
  │ 3:  │  Width: ${w}, Height: ${h}                                             │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  \recall<box>                                                          │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░   Width: 13, Height: 1
  ░
  ░   Hello, World!
  
  [End out Output]
  
  The measured content can be recalled with  \𝑟𝑒𝑐𝑎𝑙𝑙<name>. This is the foundation
  of many ::stdlib macros:
  
    ● \𝑡𝑖𝑔ℎ𝑡𝑓𝑟𝑎𝑚𝑒 measures content to compute an exact-fit frame
    ● \𝑐𝑢𝑙𝑛 measures text to render a centered underline of the right width
    ● \𝑓𝑎𝑛𝑐𝑦𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑔 measures line numbers for gutter alignment
  
            ............................................................
                           BUILDING A CENTERED UNDERLINE
  
            Here is how you might build a centered  underline from scra-
            tch using measure and layout primitives:
  
              1:  │  \measure<c,w,h>{Some Important Text}
              2:  │  \center{
              3:  │      \recall<c>\\
              4:  │      \center{\hrule[${w}]{}{═}{}}
              5:  │  }
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐖𝐢𝐝𝐭𝐡 𝐈𝐧𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐞
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Width flows down the box tree following these rules:
  
    ● \𝑠𝑒𝑡𝑤𝑖𝑑𝑡ℎ{N} sets the document-level width
    ● A box with an explicit width [N] uses that width
    ● A box without a width inherits its parent’s width
    ● In an hbox, children without explicit widths get equal shares of the
      remaining space after fixed-width children are placed
    ● auto children in an hbox expand to fill whatever is left
  
  Here is width inheritance in action:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin[40]{hbox}                                                      │
  │ 2:  │      \child[10]{Fixed 10}                                              │
  │ 3:  │      \child{Gets 15}                                                   │
  │ 4:  │      \child{Gets 15}                                                   │
  │ 5:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  [𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output:]
  
  ░ Fixed 10  Gets 15        Gets 15
  
  [End out Output]
  
  The hbox is 40 wide. One child takes 10,  leaving 30 to be split equally between
  the two remaining children (15 each).
  
  
  𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐦𝐨𝐧 𝐏𝐚𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐧𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
                                 Two-Column Layout
                               o═══════════════════o
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin{hbox}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \child{Left column content}                                       │
  │ 3:  │      \child[2]{}                                                       │
  │ 4:  │      \child{Right column content}                                      │
  │ 5:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The empty \child[2]{} creates a 2-column gutter.
  
                                 Centering Content
                               o═══════════════════o
  
  The \𝑐𝑒𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑟 stdlib macro is a thin wrapper around a vbox:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin{vbox}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \child[center]{Centered text}                                     │
  │ 3:  │  \end{vbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The \ℎ𝑐𝑒𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑟 macro centers horizontally using auto-width spacers:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin{hbox}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \child[auto]{}                                                    │
  │ 3:  │      \child[40]{Content here}                                          │
  │ 4:  │      \child[auto]{}                                                    │
  │ 5:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                    Indentation
                                  o═════════════o
  
  \𝑖𝑛𝑑𝑒𝑛𝑡 is a simple hbox with a spacer:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin{hbox}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \child[4]{}                                                       │
  │ 3:  │      \child{Indented content}                                          │
  │ 4:  │  \end{hbox}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  These patterns compose. Once you understand hbox, vbox, child, hrule, vrule, and
  intersect_rules, you can build any layout that the ::stdlib macros produce – and
  invent new ones of your own.

@label layout_guide
    \Titleframe{Layout Primitives}

    Everything you see on screen is ultimately arranged by \hyades{}'s box model.
    Prose flows into paragraphs automatically, but when you need precise spatial
    control -- columns, gutters, frames, aligned regions -- you reach for the
    layout primitives directly. Tables, lists, frames, and most ::stdlib macros
    are built on top of these primitives.

    This guide covers the core layout system from the ground up.


    \section{\textbf{The Box Model}}

    \hyades{} arranges content using two kinds of boxes:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{hbox} (horizontal box): children are placed side by side,
          left to right
        - \textbf{vbox} (vertical box): children are stacked top to bottom
    }}

    Every box is opened with \cmd{begin} and closed with \cmd{end}. Inside
    a box, each piece of content is wrapped in a \cmd{child}:

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin{hbox}
    \child[20]{Left column}
    \child[20]{Right column}
\end{hbox}
|}{%
    \begin{hbox}
        \child[20]{Left column}
        \child[20]{Right column}
    \end{hbox}
}

    In the example above, the hbox contains two children, each 20 columns
    wide. The content flows within each child independently.

    A vbox stacks children vertically:

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin[30]{vbox}
    \child{First row of content}
    \child{Second row of content}
    \child{Third row of content}
\end{vbox}
|}{%
    \begin[30]{vbox}
        \child{First row of content}
        \child{Second row of content}
        \child{Third row of content}
    \end{vbox}
}

    Notice the \verb|[30]| after \cmd{begin} -- that sets the vbox width
    to 30 columns. Without it, the box inherits the parent width.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{The \\child Command}}

    \cmd{child} is the building block inside boxes. It accepts up to two
    optional bracket arguments:

    \center{\tightframe{\verb|\child[width][alignment]{content}|}}

    \fculn{Width}

    The width can be:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - A \textbf{number}: fixed width in columns
        - \textbf{auto}: expands to fill remaining space
        - \textbf{Omitted}: inherits the parent box width (in vbox) or gets
          equal share (in hbox)
    }}

    When multiple children use \verb|auto| width, the remaining space is
    distributed equally among them:

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin[40]{hbox}
    \child[10]{Fixed}
    \child[auto]{Fills the rest}
\end{hbox}
|}{%
    \begin[40]{hbox}
        \child[10]{Fixed}
        \child[auto]{Fills the rest}
    \end{hbox}
}

    \fculn{Alignment}

    The second bracket controls horizontal alignment within the child:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{left} (default): left-aligned
        - \textbf{center}: centered
        - \textbf{right}: right-aligned
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin[30]{vbox}
    \child[left]{Left}
    \child[center]{Center}
    \child[right]{Right}
\end{vbox}
|}{%
    \begin[30]{vbox}
        \child[left]{Left}
        \child[center]{Center}
        \child[right]{Right}
    \end{vbox}
}

    Both parameters can be combined:

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin[40]{hbox}
    \child[20][right]{Right-aligned}
    \child[20][center]{Centered}
\end{hbox}
|}{%
    \begin[40]{hbox}
        \child[20][right]{Right-aligned}
        \child[20][center]{Centered}
    \end{hbox}
}

    \fculn{Vertical Alignment in hbox}

    When children in an hbox have different heights, you can control
    vertical alignment with the \cmd{begin} bracket:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{begin}[top]\{hbox\}: align children to the top (default)
        - \cmd{begin}[middle]\{hbox\}: center children vertically
        - \cmd{begin}[bottom]\{hbox\}: align children to the bottom
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin[bottom]{hbox}
    \child[20]{Short}
    \child[20]{This child
has three
lines}
\end{hbox}
|}{%
    \begin[bottom]{hbox}
        \child[20]{Short}
        \child[20]{This child
has three
lines}
    \end{hbox}
}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Horizontal Rules (\\hrule)}}

    A horizontal rule draws a line across the available width. The full
    syntax is:

    \center{\tightframe{\verb|\hrule[width]{left}{fill}{right}|}}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{width}: number or \textit{auto} (fills parent)
        - \textbf{left}: left cap character(s)
        - \textbf{fill}: repeated fill character
        - \textbf{right}: right cap character(s)
    }}

    All arguments are optional. A bare \cmd{hrule} draws a line with the
    default fill character:

    \hylst{\verb|
\hrule

\hrule[20]{<}{=}{>}

\hrule[20]{[}{.}{]}

\hrule[20]{o}{═}{o}
|}{%
    \indented{
        \hrule

        \hrule[20]{<}{=}{>}

        \hrule[20]{[}{.}{]}

        \hrule[20]{o}{═}{o}
    }
}

    Inside a vbox, an \textit{auto}-width hrule stretches to the box width:

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin[30]{vbox}
    \child{Some content above}
    \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}
    \child{Some content below}
\end{vbox}
|}{%
    \begin[30]{vbox}
        \child{Some content above}
        \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}
        \child{Some content below}
    \end{vbox}
}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Vertical Rules (\\vrule)}}

    A vertical rule draws a line down the height of the available space.
    The full syntax is:

    \center{\tightframe{\verb|\vrule[width]{top}{fill}{bottom}|}}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{width}: fixed or \textit{auto}
        - \textbf{top}: top cap character
        - \textbf{fill}: repeated fill character
        - \textbf{bottom}: bottom cap character
    }}

    When placed in an hbox with \verb|auto| height, the vrule stretches
    to match the tallest sibling:

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin{hbox}
    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{╭}{│}{╰}}
    \child[20]{Line one
Line two
Line three}
    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{╮}{│}{╯}}
\end{hbox}
|}{%
    \begin{hbox}
        \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{╭}{│}{╰}}
        \child[20]{Line one
Line two
Line three}
        \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{╮}{│}{╯}}
    \end{hbox}
}

    This is, in fact, exactly how the \cmd{frame} stdlib macro works
    internally -- two vrules on the sides, two hrules on the top and bottom,
    and the content in the middle.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Combining hbox and vbox}}

    Real layouts nest boxes. A common pattern is an hbox of columns, each
    containing a vbox:

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin[40]{hbox}
    \child[20]{
        \begin{vbox}
            \child{Header A}
            \child{\hrule}
            \child{Data 1}
            \child{Data 2}
        \end{vbox}
    }
    \child[20]{
        \begin{vbox}
            \child{Header B}
            \child{\hrule}
            \child{Data 3}
            \child{Data 4}
        \end{vbox}
    }
\end{hbox}
|}{%
    \begin[40]{hbox}
        \child[20]{
            \begin{vbox}
                \child{Header A}
                \child{\hrule}
                \child{Data 1}
                \child{Data 2}
            \end{vbox}
        }
        \child[20]{
            \begin{vbox}
                \child{Header B}
                \child{\hrule}
                \child{Data 3}
                \child{Data 4}
            \end{vbox}
        }
    \end{hbox}
}

    The \cmd{table} system macro generates exactly this kind of nested
    box structure, with added frame characters and junction handling.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Junction Handling (\\intersect\_rules)}}

    When horizontal and vertical rules cross, their characters must be
    replaced with proper junction characters. The \cmd{intersect\_rules}
    command does this automatically:

    \hylst{\verb|
\intersect_rules{
\begin[20]{vbox}
    \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}
    \child{
        \begin{hbox}
            \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
            \child[auto]{Cell A}
            \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
            \child[auto]{Cell B}
            \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
        \end{hbox}
    }
    \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}
\end{vbox}
}
|}{%
    \intersect_rules{
    \begin[20]{vbox}
        \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}
        \child{
            \begin{hbox}
                \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
                \child[auto]{Cell A}
                \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
                \child[auto]{Cell B}
                \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
            \end{hbox}
        }
        \child{\hrule[auto]{}{─}{}}
    \end{vbox}
    }
}

    Without \cmd{intersect\_rules}, the ─ and │ characters would overlap
    rather than form proper ┌ ┬ ┐ ├ ┼ ┤ └ ┴ ┘ junctions. The junction
    fixup pass scans every cell, checks its four neighbors for line arms,
    and replaces the character with the correct junction glyph.

    This works with single, double, bold, and mixed line styles. It also
    preserves intentionally-placed characters (like rounded corners
    ╭ ╮ ╰ ╯) when their arms already match the expected junction.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Measuring Content}}

    The \cmd{measure} command renders content in an invisible infinite
    space, measures its dimensions, and stores it for later recall:

    \center{\tightframe{\verb|\measure<c,w,h>{content}|}}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{c}: name under which the rendered content is stored
        - \textbf{w}: variable receiving the measured width
        - \textbf{h}: variable receiving the measured height
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
\measure<box,w,h>{Hello, World!}

Width: ${w}, Height: ${h}

\recall<box>
|}{%
    \measure<box,w,h>{Hello, World!}
    \indented{
        Width: ${w}, Height: ${h}

        \recall<box>
    }
}

    The measured content can be recalled with \cmd{recall}\<name\>.
    This is the foundation of many ::stdlib macros:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{tightframe} measures content to compute an exact-fit frame
        - \cmd{culn} measures text to render a centered underline of the
          right width
        - \cmd{fancylisting} measures line numbers for gutter alignment
    }}

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{BUILDING A CENTERED UNDERLINE}
    Here is how you might build a centered underline from scratch using
    measure and layout primitives:

    \listing{
\verb|\measure<c,w,h>{Some Important Text}
\center{
    \recall<c>\\
    \center{\hrule[${w}]{}{═}{}}
}|}
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Width Inheritance}}

    Width flows down the box tree following these rules:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{setwidth}\{N\} sets the document-level width
        - A box with an explicit width \verb|[N]| uses that width
        - A box without a width inherits its parent's width
        - In an hbox, children without explicit widths get equal shares of
          the remaining space after fixed-width children are placed
        - \verb|auto| children in an hbox expand to fill whatever is left
    }}

    Here is width inheritance in action:

    \hylst{\verb|
\begin[40]{hbox}
    \child[10]{Fixed 10}
    \child{Gets 15}
    \child{Gets 15}
\end{hbox}
|}{%
    \begin[40]{hbox}
        \child[10]{Fixed 10}
        \child{Gets 15}
        \child{Gets 15}
    \end{hbox}
}

    The hbox is 40 wide. One child takes 10, leaving 30 to be split
    equally between the two remaining children (15 each).


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Common Patterns}}

    \fculn{Two-Column Layout}

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\begin{hbox}
    \child{Left column content}
    \child[2]{}
    \child{Right column content}
\end{hbox}
|}

    The empty \verb|\child[2]{}| creates a 2-column gutter.

    \fculn{Centering Content}

    The \cmd{center} stdlib macro is a thin wrapper around a vbox:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\begin{vbox}
    \child[center]{Centered text}
\end{vbox}
|}

    The \cmd{hcenter} macro centers horizontally using auto-width spacers:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\begin{hbox}
    \child[auto]{}
    \child[40]{Content here}
    \child[auto]{}
\end{hbox}
|}

    \fculn{Indentation}

    \cmd{indent} is a simple hbox with a spacer:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\begin{hbox}
    \child[4]{}
    \child{Indented content}
\end{hbox}
|}

    These patterns compose. Once you understand hbox, vbox, child, hrule,
    vrule, and intersect\_rules, you can build any layout that the ::stdlib
    macros produce -- and invent new ones of your own.

@end

#target_prefix " "

#before_each
    \linebreaker{greedy}
    \setwidth{80}
    \setunicode{true}
    \setmathitalic{true}

    \macro<\indented{content}>{\indent[2]{${content}}}
    \macro<\cmd{x}>{\textbackslash{}\textit{${x}}}

    
    \macro<\leftbar{c}{n}>{
       ░ ${c}
    }
    
    %%% Renders hy as source and rend as an example rendered output
    \macro<\hylst{hy}{rend}>{%
        \fancylisting{${hy}}
        [\hyades{} Output:]
        \lineroutine<leftbar>{${rend}}
        [End out Output]
    }

    \macro<\didyouknow{content}>{
        \vskip{1}
        \hcenter[60]{
        \hrule{}{.}{}
        ${content}
        \hrule{}{.}{}
        }
    }
#end
